an API change posing some risks. I need to ensure that when preparing the Forge workflow, the generated tests include the current existing tests. It seems crucial that the driver can handle the setup to avoid issues during execution. I want to make sure everything is clearly defined and operational to prevent any unexpected problems down the line.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"no_action\",\n  \"summary\": \"No extra deterministic setup is needed: org.eclipse.jetty:jetty-webapp:9.4.0.RC1 brings the required Jetty runtime stack transitively, including jetty-xml, jetty-servlet, jetty-security, jetty-server, javax.servlet-api, jetty-http, jetty-io, and jetty-util. Meaningful coverage is reachable with in-process WebAppContext/WebAppClassLoader tests using temporary webapp files and localhost connectors; no Docker service, extra Maven dependency, environment variable, or system property is required.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"The reported javac failure is caused by a Jetty 9.4.0.RC1 API change in WebAppClassLoader.Context, not by missing setup. Tests that keep custom Context implementations must update isSystemClass/isServerClass to Class<?> signatures and implement isServerResource(String, URL) and isSystemResource(String, URL).\",\n    \"Optional Jetty features such as JMX or JSP/annotation-heavy webapps may require optional modules, but they are not required for meaningful jetty-webapp coverage of descriptor processing, WebAppContext startup, static content serving, and classloader behavior.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0d50bd1b131e96e8016a42b04178048195b77d9fcecb4f18a5\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1415, "output": 1316, "cacheRead": 30208, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 32939, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": 